This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:07 PM Defendant Larry Eugene Aiken Jr appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Angela M Wilson in court for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Ryan Reed appears in court on behalf of the defendant. Attorney Reid verifies a current address. Notes receipt of the complaint and enter plea of not guilty on count 2. State asks for $1,000 signature bond with conditions of no contact with victim 1, her son, and the address of the victim. State notes that the defendant does not have a criminal history, thus no FTA. Attorney Reid notes that the defendant is a lifelong resident of the Twin Ports, has employment, and has strong familial ties to the area. Agreeable to signature bond. Court orders $1,000 signature bond. Conditions that there is no contact with Victim 1, he son, or the victim's residence.
